  <p>
    "They would cut an 
    <span class="term">Indian's hands
      <span class="popup">Refers to the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.</span>
    </span> and leave them dangling by a shred of skin ... [and] they would test their 
    <span class="term">swords
      <span class="popup">Weapons with sharp blades used by soldiers and captains.</span>
    </span> and their 
    <span class="term">manly strength
      <span class="popup">The physical power and skill of the Spanish captains.</span>
    </span> on captured Indians and place 
    <span class="term">bets
      <span class="popup">Gambles made on who could kill the most or perform violent acts.</span>
    </span> on the slicing off of heads or cutting of bodies in half with one blow. ... [One] cruel 
    <span class="term">captain
      <span class="popup">A leader of Spanish forces committing atrocities.</span>
    </span> traveled over many 
    <span class="term">leagues
      <span class="popup">Units of distance used in the 16th century; roughly 3 miles per league.</span>
    </span>, capturing all the 
    <span class="term">Indians
      <span class="popup">The local Indigenous people encountered by the Spanish.</span>
    </span> he could find. Since the Indians would not tell him who their new 
    <span class="term">lord
      <span class="popup">Referring to a ruler or leader the Spanish wanted the Indians to obey.</span>
    </span> was, he cut off the hands of some and threw others to the 
    <span class="term">dogs
      <span class="popup">Used to attack or kill prisoners.</span>
    </span>, and thus they were torn to pieces."
  </p>

  <p style="text-align:right; font-style: italic;">
    - Bartolomé De Las Casas
  </p>

